**Example (JavaScript):**
```javascript
// JavaScript (Duck Typing)
function makeSound(creature) {
  // We don't check if 'creature' is a Dog or a Cat class.
  // We just check if it has a 'quack' method.
  if (typeof creature.quack === 'function') {
    creature.quack();
  }
}

**Example:**
```typescript
// Define the required structure (Interface)
interface Quacker {
  quack(): void;
}

// Function expects a Quacker
function makeSound(creature: Quacker) {
  creature.quack();
}

// Class A
class Duck {
  quack() { console.log("Quack"); }
}

// Class B (Not a Duck, but has the same structure)
class Robot {
  quack() { console.log("Beep"); }
}

**1.** A computer-implemented method for issuing a community tax certificate and related permits as a digital credential, comprising:
    (a) receiving, via a user digital wallet, a request for a community tax certificate comprising user identity data and asset declaration data;
    (b) transmitting said data to a Machine Learning (ML) Inference Engine configured to:
        (i) execute a regression algorithm to calculate a tax liability amount based on historical tax data and current regulatory parameters; and
        (ii) execute an anomaly detection algorithm to generate a fraud risk score;
    (c) if the fraud risk score is below a predetermined threshold, automatically generating a payment smart contract on a blockchain network specifying the calculated tax liability amount;
    (d) receiving a payment transaction from the user digital wallet to a government treasury wallet via the blockchain network;
    (e) upon confirmation of the payment transaction on the blockchain, automatically triggering a minting function within the smart contract to generate a Verifiable Credential (VC) representing the community tax certificate, wherein the VC is cryptographically signed by a government issuer key; and
    (f) transmitting the generated VC to the user digital wallet for secure storage.

**6.** A system for automated issuance of government permits, comprising:
    (a) a processor and memory storing instructions that, when executed, cause the system to:
    (i) interface with a user digital wallet to receive a permit application;
    (ii) process the application through a neural network trained on historical permit data to determine eligibility and calculate fees;
    (iii) interact with a blockchain network to execute a smart contract for fee collection; and
    (iv) issue a cryptographically signed Verifiable Credential upon successful fee collection;
    (b) a blockchain node configured to maintain a ledger of transaction hashes and a revocation registry for issued credentials; and
    (c) a secure API gateway connecting the system to legacy government databases for real-time data validation.

